 couched largely in terms of superpower confrontations during a crisis whether the focus is on the major powers or on developing nations with ballistic missiles and probable nuclear weapons capability stability in those who handle weapons and effective safeguards on use are essential preventive measures the united states and the ussr have been careful to guard against unauthorized launch all nuclear nations have been concerned with retaining ultimate control of nuclear weapons in civilian hands with monitoring the reliability and stability of the forces that handle the weapons and with preventing weapons from coming into the possession of outsiders in 1986 an analysis of the sources of human instability in those who handle nuclear weapons concluded that thousands of unstable individuals were involved in minding our missiles 1 the present paper serves as an update on the problem and links it to potential areas of increasing risk as the world changes download pdf+ complete modified june 2004 pdf hum_rel_nukes pdf 2.4 mb topics nuclear safety and security united states search cisac publications everything publications of interest nuclear weapons safety after the cold war technical and organizational opportunities for improvement scott d sagan cisac 1994 nuclear weapons safety and trident issues and options john r harvey stefan michalowski cisac 1993 notes on trident nuclear weapons safety john r harvey anne yuan lin cisac 1995 security issues in the handling and disposition of fissionable material herbert l abrams dan pollak cisac 1993 support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 9625 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
